## {{ rule.title }}

[26 U.S.C. § 1](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1&num=0&edition=prelim) imposes graduated tax rates on taxable income; [§ 1(h)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1&num=0&edition=prelim) layers preferential rates (0/15/20 %) on net long-term capital gain and qualified dividends. The [Form 1040](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1040) line 16 *Qualified Dividends and Capital Gain Tax Worksheet* implements the ordering: it splits taxable income into an ordinary stack (taxed at [§ 1](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1&num=0&edition=prelim) brackets) and a preferential stack (taxed at [§ 1(h)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1&num=0&edition=prelim) rates), then adds the two pieces.

{% set tax = rule.outputs[0].value | from_json -%}
For 2025:

- Taxable income from US25-08: **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.stage.taxable_income"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**
- Preferential capital base (long-term gain + qualified dividends, from US25-06): **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.stage.preferential_capital_base"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**
- Ordinary stack (taxable income minus preferential base): **{{ tax.taxable_ordinary_income_usd | money(currency="USD") }}** — taxed using the 2025 [§ 1](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1&num=0&edition=prelim) brackets, producing **{{ tax.ordinary_tax_component_usd | money(currency="USD") }}**.
- Preferential stack: **{{ tax.qualified_dividend_tax_component_usd | money(currency="USD") }}** of tax on qualified dividends and long-term gains under [§ 1(h)](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1&num=0&edition=prelim).

Adding the two components gives **regular tax before credits = {{ tax.regular_tax_before_credits_usd | money(currency="USD") }}** for [Form 1040](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1040) line 16. This is the base against which the foreign tax credit (US25-19) and treaty re-sourcing credit (US25-18) are applied.

